to haste, or hasten, intrans. or trans. of what is done in haste. Festino,
1; prŏpĕro, 1; mātūro, 1; cĕlĕro, 1; accelero.—Tullus hastens to invade
the Sabine territory. Occupat Tullus in agrum Sabinum transire. Liv.
—There was no need for making haste. Erat nihil cur properato opus
esset. Cic.—A thousand ships were made ready in haste. Mille naves
properatæ. Tac.
hastily, i. e. rashly. Tĕmĕre, inconsīdĕrāte.

body. L. Catilina fuit magnâ vi et animi et corporis. Sall.—Where-

even if it has not them in great abundance, is not usually destitute. Bons

omnino caret. Cic.
